 music. Turino uses the musical traditions of Conima, Peru as a unifying thread, tracing them through the varying lives of Conimeos in different locales. He reveals how music both sustains and creates meaning for a people struggling amid the dramatic social upheavals of contemporary Peru. Moving Away from Silence contains detailed interpretations based on comparative field research of Conimeo musical performance, rehearsals, composition, and festivals in the highlands and Lima. The volume will be of great importance to students of Latin American music and culture as well as ethnomusicological and ethnographic theory and method.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFolk musiczPeruzConima (District)xHistory and criticism. 0aFolk musiczPeruzLimaxHistory and criticism. 0aRural-urban migrationzPeru. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  amusic, flute, andean panpipe, altiplano, peru, urban, migration, folklore, culture, tradition, rural, migrants, highland, villages, politics, ethnography, lima, festival, composition, rehearsals, performance, latin america, community, competition, aesthetics, instruments, qhantati ururi, youth, centro social conima, conimenos, nonfiction.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1990-1999z978311066785140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226816951423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226816951/original  a978-3-11-066785-1  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1990-1999c1990d1999  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles